`crates/steno/src/editor/` models a scripted keystroke stream against an editor buffer and converts between three representations of that stream: the `Event` IR, a running buffer state, and Plover's `{^...^}`/`{#...}` dictionary-entry text format. Depending on this module gets you `interpret` (run events → final buffer/cursor/mark state), `movement_events` (compute keystrokes to reposition a cursor backward to an offset), and `serialize`/`escape_text` (events → Plover value string) — the crate's editor API surface, all re-exported from `mod.rs`.

The shared coupling point is the `Event` enum (`Text(String)`, `Key { key, n }`, `Mark(u32)`) defined in `mod.rs`: `interpret.rs`, `movement.rs`, and `serialize.rs` all pattern-match its exact three-variant shape, and `sim.rs` is driven one `Event` at a time by `interpret.rs` via `apply_key`/character insertion. `KeyName::name()` (also in `mod.rs`) is the single source of the literal key names that appear in `serialize.rs`'s `{#...}` groups. Character-classification helpers (`auto_close_of`, `ends_with_opener`, `is_auto_close`, `is_quote`) live in `mod.rs` but are consulted only by `sim.rs`; adding a new bracket/quote type or a new `Behaviors` field means touching `mod.rs` plus every read site in `sim.rs` (and auditing `interpret.rs`/`movement.rs`), since nothing enforces that threading automatically. The `Behaviors` profile presets (`PLAIN`, `SMART`, `SMART_INDENT`) are exercised by round-trip tests elsewhere that call `interpret(emit(t, B), B)`.

Per-file roles: `mod.rs` is the type/constant home and API surface; `sim.rs` is the internal (non-reexported) stateful buffer engine reachable only via `crate::editor::sim`; `interpret.rs` drives `sim.rs` through an event stream and packages the result into `EditorState`, discarding all marks except `%0`; `movement.rs` generates key sequences for backward-only cursor repositioning, independent of `sim`/`interpret`; `serialize.rs` renders an event stream to Plover's text format, independent of `sim` entirely. A cross-cutting invariant: all cursor/position math throughout (`sim.rs`, `movement.rs`) is in character offsets (`Vec<char>` / char counts), never bytes.